    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-03T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-03T06:00:00-05:00" n="814"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d814">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.6363 Import Law/12: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-03T11:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 3, 1928—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 3—9:17 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>57. Embassy’s telegram No. 48, February 17, 8 p.m.,<note n="48" xml:id="d814fn48"
                        >Not printed.</note> and despatch 8343 of February 18. The following
                    favorable change has taken place since then:</p>
                <p>Prime Minister Poincaré and Foreign Minister Briand, appearing yesterday before
                    the petroleum committee of the French Chamber of Deputies, opposed the
                    objectionable amendments to the petroleum importation bill which had been
                    adopted by the said committee.</p>
                <p>M. Briand, especially, took a very strong position which was fully in accord with
                    his previous assurances to me.</p>
                <p>American and British oil companies may, as a result, now be heard on Monday by
                    the committee. The amendments having been withdrawn by their committee authors,
                    the bill in its original form will come before the Chamber of Deputies on
                    Tuesday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
